From: Eric Lundby <Eric.Lundby@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 7 Apr 2026 12:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] S_mayberelocate: truncate after NUL-padded prefix

Conda's binary prefix replacement can pad shorter paths with NUL inside the
fixed-width literal embedded at build time. STR_WITH_LEN still passes the
compile-time length, so that padding becomes part of the SV and breaks joins
for module paths. Truncate at the first NUL before using the string.

---
 perl.c | 10 ++++++++++
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+)

diff --git a/perl.c b/perl.c
--- a/perl.c
+++ b/perl.c
@@ -5001,6 +5001,16 @@
 
     PERL_ARGS_ASSERT_MAYBERELOCATE;
     assert(len > 0);
+
+    /* After in-place prefix replacement, `dir` may be shorter than the
+     * compile-time STR_WITH_LEN length, with NUL fill.  Do not let that
+     * padding become part of the SV (breaks joins for module paths). */
+    {
+        const char *const nul_pos = (const char *) memchr(dir, '\0', len);
+
+        if (nul_pos)
+            len = (STRLEN)(nul_pos - dir);
+    }
 
     /* I am not convinced that this is valid when PERLLIB_MANGLE is
        defined to so something (in os2/os2.c), but the code has been
